(d) [20pt] Create new variables with functions of existing variables - mutate()

  1. For the non-canceled flights, use the mutate() function to create a new variable flight_time which equals arr_time - dep_time. Make a scatter plot to compare flight_time with air_time.

ANSWER

# new variable flight time in not_canceled
flights_time <- mutate(not_canceled, flight_time = arr_time - dep_time)

# plot the data with x = flight time and y = air time
ggplot(data = flights_time) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = flight_time, y = air_time))

  1. What do you expect to see? What do you see? Why are there negative values in flight_time?

ANSWER There are negative values because if a flight arrives after midnight, i.e after 0000, the departure time will be greater than it thus giving a negative value.

  1. Fix your R code to correct the negative values in flight_time. Make the scatter plot again.

Hint: The lubridate package would be helpful. Check out our textbook Chapter 16 “Dates and times”

library(lubridate)
## Warning: package 'lubridate' was built under R version 4.0.5

## 
##     date, intersect, setdiff, union
flights_time <- mutate(flights_time, 
                       new_arr_time = make_datetime(year, month, day, arr_time%/%100, arr_time%%100),
                       new_dep_time = make_datetime(year, month, day, dep_time%/%100, dep_time%%100),
                       new_flight_time = new_arr_time - new_dep_time)

for(i in 1:length(flights_time)){
  if(flights_time$new_flight_time[i] < 0){
    flights_time$new_flight_time[i] <- (flights_time$new_flight_time[i] + 60*24) * (-1)
  }
}

ggplot(data = flights_time) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = new_flight_time, y = air_time))

(f.1) [25pt] Daily flight cancellation rate

  1. Suppose we are interested in studying the number of canceled flights per day. Is there a pattern? Make a scatter plot of the proportion of canceled flights per day (x-axis) vs average delay per day (y-axis). Use point size to represent the number of originally scheduled flights on each day. Add a smoothed fitted line to your scatter plot. Is the proportion of canceled flights related to the average delay?

Hint: Group flights (do not use not_canceled) by both month and day, so that your scatter plot has 365 points in total.

ANSWER

canceled <- 
  flights %>%
  group_by(month, day) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
            canceled_flights = sum(is.na(dep_delay)),
            canceled_proportion = canceled_flights/count,
            avg_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

  1. Suppose we are interested in identifying the carriers with the least/worst delays. To disentangle the effects of bad airports vs. bad carriers, we group all non-canceled flights by both carrier and dest, then calculate the average arrival delay for each carrier and dest pair. Make side-by-side boxplots to compare the distribution of average arrival delay among different carriers. Flip your boxplot to have horizontal display and rank all boxes by their median values.

ANSWER

# group by carrier and destination then calculate mean delay
not_canceled <- 
  not_canceled %>%
  group_by(carrier, dest) %>%
  mutate(avg_delay = mean(arr_delay))
# splot data using median to find the least/worst average delay
ggplot(data = not_canceled) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = reorder(carrier, avg_delay, FUN = median), y = avg_delay)) +
  coord_flip()

ANSWER It looks like the carrier with the worst delays was F9 and the carrier with the least delays was AS.
